<DOC><DOCNO> AP880401-0097 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1040EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Carlucci     04-01 0154</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Carlucci,0159</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Defense Secretary In Morocco</HEAD><DATELINE>MARRAKECH, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci saidtoday the United States would continue its close cooperation withthe moderate Arab government of Morocco.   Carlucci began a three-day visit that was to include tours ofMoroccan military bases. On Sunday, he will fly to India and thenvisit Pakistan and Tunisia before returning to Washington.   On arrival, he praised ``the close links that have united ourtwo countries in the course of the past two centuries.''   ``I am convinced that this cooperation with continue in thefuture in the interest of our two countries and our two peoples,''he said.   American aid to Morocco in 1987 was $131 million, $35 million ofwhich was to help the government in its 13-year-long war againstPolisario guerrillas fighting for the independence of the formerSpanish Sahara.   The defense secretary is to return to Washington on April 9.</TEXT></DOC>